        // for each left value we've moved past, the right value at the time we moved past it.
        // rightWhenLeft[a] = the value of right when left moved past a
        // Then: rightWhenLeft[a] - a <= maxLength for all a < left
        // And: no unique substring starting at a extends to rightWhenLeft[a]+1
        //   because s[rightWhenLeft[a]] was in {s[a], ..., s[rightWhenLeft[a]-1]}
        //   (which is why we moved left forward)
        // So max unique starting at a has length <= rightWhenLeft[a] - a <= maxLength.
        //
        // But wait: s[rightWhenLeft[a]] was in {s[left_at_that_time], ..., s[rightWhenLeft[a]-1]}
        // Not necessarily in {s[a], ..., s[rightWhenLeft[a]-1]}.
        // So a unique substring [a..rightWhenLeft[a]+1) might still have all distinct chars
        // if the duplicate was between left_at_that_time (>= a) and rightWhenLeft[a].
        //
        // Actually no: left_at_that_time might be > a when we're processing the left-move.
        // The right only increases; left also only increases. When left is first moved past a,
        // right has some value R, and s[R] was in {s[a], ..., s[R-1]} (since a <= left <= left_at_move_time
