        // but there could be a longer unique substring [a..R') with R' > R that happens to avoid the
        // duplicate that was at R. But that's impossible: if [a..R) has all distinct and s[R] is in
        // {s[a],...,s[R-1]}, then [a..R+1) does NOT have all distinct. So the maximal unique substring
        // starting at a extending right has length exactly R - a.
        //
        // The issue: we DON'T have s[R] in {s[a], ..., s[R-1]}.
        // We have s[R] in {s[left], ..., s[R-1]} where left >= a.
        // So s[R] is in {s[left], ..., s[R-1]} but might not be in {s[a], ..., s[left-1]}.
        //
        // So [a..R+1) might still be unique! The duplicate was only with the window [left..R).
        //
        // This means rightWhenLeft[a] is NOT necessarily the bound for unique substrings starting at a.
        //
        // OK so the standard approach is different. Let me think about what invariant actually holds.
        //
        // Claim: the right answer is to track, for each position a that left has passed,
        // that s[a] appears again in s[a+1..right). I.e., there's a duplicate involving position a
        // somewhere in [a..right).
